[The previous EIA outbreak in Germany (Bavaria) was reported by Germany to the OIE in January 2017 (20170119.4777963); earlier cases had been recorded during 2015. Subscribers are referred to the following commentary by Mod.CRD, as included in the said post:

"Equine infectious anaemia (EIA) is a persistent viral infection of equids. The causative agent, EIA virus (EIAV) is a lentivirus in the family Retroviridae, subfamily Orthoretrovirinae. EIA can be diagnosed on the basis of clinical signs, pathological lesions, serology, and molecular methods. Infected horses remain viraemic carriers for life and, with very rare exceptions, yield a positive serological test result.

"Antibody response usually persists and antibody-positive animals, older than 6-8 months, are identified as virus carriers (below 6-8 months of age, serological reactions can be due to maternal antibodies; status can be confirmed by molecular techniques). Infected equids are potential virus reservoirs. Biting flies are mechanical vectors for the virus in nature." (http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/2.05.06_EIA.pdf)

Between December 2014 and December 2015, 7 outbreaks of EIA were reported in Germany. These outbreaks were located in the provinces of Saxony (3) and Bavaria (4). A total of 13 cases were diagnosed from a susceptible population of 160 animals (equidae). All affected animals (cases) were destroyed. The event was resolved on November 2015. See the final report, dated 17 Dec 2015, at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/temp/reports/en_fup_0000019368_20151218_125041.pdf.

EIA virus is not considered a risk for human health".

An interactive OIE map presenting EIA cases in Europe since Jan 2015 is available at http://tinyurl.com/y86etwcq (click on Europe, zoom in).

Maps of Germany can be seen at http://tinyurl.com/ycbyuk5g and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5094162,37159.
Verden is a district in the centre of Lower Saxony (Niedersachsen), Germany (map at http://tinyurl.com/ycys7lec). - Mod.AS]
